### 2.3 ABAC with AWS IAM (Optional)

AWS IAM natively supports ABAC via **tags**. This is one of the most common real-world ABAC implementations.

#### Step 1 — Create Users with Tags

```bash
# Create IAM users with department tags (simulating ABAC attributes)
aws iam create-user --user-name alice-nurse \
    --tags Key=Department,Value=Oncology Key=Role,Value=Nurse

aws iam create-user --user-name bob-physician \
    --tags Key=Department,Value=Oncology Key=Role,Value=Physician

echo "✅ IAM users created with attribute tags"
```

#### Step 2 — Create an ABAC Policy Using Condition Keys

Save as `abac-s3-policy.json`:

```json
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "AllowAccessIfTagsMatch",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "s3:GetObject",
        "s3:PutObject"
      ],
      "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::patient-records-*/*",
      "Condition": {
        "StringEquals": {
          "aws:PrincipalTag/Department": "${s3:prefix}",
          "aws:PrincipalTag/Role": "Physician"
        }
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

> **What this does:** A user can only access S3 objects in a prefix that matches their `Department` tag, and only if their `Role` tag is `Physician`. This is pure ABAC — no role assignments in IAM, just tags.

#### Step 3 — Tag the S3 Buckets/Objects

```bash
# Create buckets per department
aws s3 mb s3://patient-records-oncology
aws s3 mb s3://patient-records-cardiology

# Tag the buckets
aws s3api put-bucket-tagging \
    --bucket patient-records-oncology \
    --tagging 'TagSet=[{Key=Department,Value=Oncology}]'
```

